From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Mon, 20 Jul 2026 18:16:56 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 56/56] web-app: render group/contact invite links as a card
 with a View button
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

An https://i.delta.chat/#… invite link in a message is a long, unreadable
fingerprint URL, even though the one thing a reader cares about — which
group / channel / contact it is for — is right there in the URL fragment
(g= / b= / n= / a= params). Render such links as a compact card instead:
letter avatar, a 'Group invitation' / 'Channel invitation' / 'Contact
invitation' label, the decoded name, and a View button. The whole card is
the link; clicking keeps the existing behavior (processQr → the usual
join/chat confirmation dialog).

The name is parsed from the link alone, mirroring core's qr.rs decoding
('+' as space, trailing '_' as ellipsis) — deliberately NOT via core's
checkQr, which would create a hidden contact as a side effect just for
rendering a message. The name is sender-controlled and cosmetic; the
confirmation dialog stays the actual decision point, and the raw URL
remains visible as the link title. Unparseable fragments fall back to
today's plain link.

colorFromString moves from the Public Bots dialog to utils/ so both spots
derive a stable avatar color for names that have no core contact.

Right-click 'Copy link' previously only appeared when the click landed on
the anchor element itself; the card's child elements (name, avatar, View)
broke that. The message context menu now resolves the clicked element to
its enclosing anchor via closest('a'), which also covers future labeled
links with formatting in the label.
